1
00:00:03,676 --> 00:00:33,243
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambodasa Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambodasa Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambodasa Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and self-awakened one.

2
00:00:35,518 --> 00:00:40,165
Okay, so I thought we'd do another little exercise on our evening.

3
00:00:42,429 --> 00:00:44,732
We've done a few in the past couple of years.

4
00:00:46,494 --> 00:00:48,518
And this one is basically based on the body.

5
00:00:48,639 --> 00:00:54,807
So the body in the Buddha's teaching is, well, it's just part and parcel of it.

6
00:00:55,008 --> 00:00:57,151
Yeah.

7
00:00:57,170 --> 00:01:02,658
And he wants us really to undermine our identification with it, our possession of it.

8
00:01:02,679 --> 00:01:04,361
You know, we'll say things like,

9
00:01:04,847 --> 00:01:06,549
I have a headache.

10
00:01:06,750 --> 00:01:07,831
See, I have a headache.

11
00:01:08,432 --> 00:01:09,853
So somebody has a headache.

12
00:01:10,635 --> 00:01:11,796
But of course, I am ill.

13
00:01:12,257 --> 00:01:17,584
So there's a bit of confusion there as to how we relate to this body of ours.

14
00:01:19,006 --> 00:01:34,364
And one thing he puts to us is to really come to terms with our relationship to the body, especially, specifically those parts that we find unattractive, repulsive even, disgusting.

15
00:01:35,037 --> 00:01:35,617
Almost.

16
00:01:38,882 --> 00:01:40,325
And there are three parts to this.

17
00:01:40,385 --> 00:01:47,936
First of all, we begin by recognizing the preciousness of the human life.

18
00:01:49,379 --> 00:01:58,132
And then we do this business of relating better to the body as a mammal, right?

19
00:01:58,254 --> 00:02:01,078
I mean, we are animals at the physical level.

20
00:02:02,206 --> 00:02:08,274
And then to find a way to balance that through the process of gratitude.

21
00:02:10,796 --> 00:02:18,526
Okay, so if we think about the preciousness of this birth, the Buddha gives us a metaphor.

22
00:02:18,926 --> 00:02:23,673
He says, suppose there's a turtle in the ocean and it only comes up to breathe once every hundred years.

23
00:02:24,674 --> 00:02:26,896
And in the whole ocean, there's only one log.

24
00:02:28,193 --> 00:02:33,104
How fortunate to come to the service and bump his head against that block.

25
00:02:33,123 --> 00:02:37,653
So that's how fortunate we are to become human beings.

26
00:02:37,954 --> 00:02:41,983
And of course, the great fortune is to have come across the Dharma.

27
00:02:44,090 --> 00:02:46,133
So obviously we can't be here without the body.

28
00:02:46,633 --> 00:02:47,375
That's simple enough.

29
00:02:48,576 --> 00:02:53,885
It's through the senses, through the senses of the body, the outer senses that we experience the world.

30
00:02:54,507 --> 00:02:56,430
And everything that we learn comes through them.

31
00:02:56,811 --> 00:02:57,031
Yeah.

32
00:02:57,131 --> 00:02:58,593
What we hear, what we see and so on.

33
00:03:00,276 --> 00:03:05,724
It's through the body that we relate, we communicate, we establish relationships, we express ourselves.

34
00:03:07,268 --> 00:03:08,729
Art, you know, things like that.

35
00:03:10,296 --> 00:03:13,461
It's through the body we work for the benefit of ourselves and others.

36
00:03:13,981 --> 00:03:17,407
So there's a model element there, which is, of course, our karma.

37
00:03:18,669 --> 00:03:23,795
And finally, in virtually all techniques, the body is included.

38
00:03:23,855 --> 00:03:25,157
It has to be because it's there.

39
00:03:25,198 --> 00:03:28,483
You have to acknowledge that the body is here.

40
00:03:29,403 --> 00:03:31,426
So in our practice, of course, it's the breath.

41
00:03:34,747 --> 00:03:49,100
Okay, so having acknowledged that, having acknowledged the preciousness of the human birth, we can now just spend a moment apologizing to the body for what we may have done to it, for what harm we may have done to it.

42
00:03:49,200 --> 00:03:58,709
So we might have put it in dangerous situations, we might have put substances in it which has not done it very good, and so on and so forth.

43
00:03:59,669 --> 00:04:02,712
So if you wish, you can repeat after me this little verse.

44
00:04:06,776 --> 00:04:18,911
Whatever harm I have done to you, that's the body, in thought, word and deed, by way of greed, aversion, fear and delusion.

45
00:04:27,401 --> 00:04:36,091
Intentionally or unintentionally, I am heartily sorry for it.

46
00:04:37,252 --> 00:04:46,064
And I determined from this day on to treat you with due care and respect.

47
00:04:54,132 --> 00:05:04,745
Okay, so now we can get on to the 32 parts that the Buddha goes through, which is the unpleasantness, the unattractiveness, the repulsiveness, call it what you want, of the body.

48
00:05:05,788 --> 00:05:09,514
And here's a verse from the Dhammapada.

49
00:05:10,074 --> 00:05:20,968
Knowing this body is like foam, fully awake to its mirage-like nature, cutting off Mara's flowers, one goes unseen by the king of death.

50
00:05:22,411 --> 00:05:23,812
So the body is foam.

51
00:05:23,994 --> 00:05:25,675
There's no reality to it.

52
00:05:26,136 --> 00:05:28,459
It's a mirage-like nature.

53
00:05:28,560 --> 00:05:32,504
It's something that is also an extension of our minds.

54
00:05:33,480 --> 00:05:35,204
cutting off Mara's flowers.

55
00:05:35,464 --> 00:05:40,553
So Mara is not the sort of torturing devil of Christianity.

56
00:05:40,613 --> 00:05:50,552
He's more the tempter that you find in Islam, tempting you to devote your life to sensual pleasure.

57
00:05:52,637 --> 00:05:54,540
And that's why he offers flowers.

58
00:05:54,761 --> 00:05:56,062
They're attractive, you see.

59
00:05:57,004 --> 00:06:06,776
Now, if we can get rid of all that as an attachment, then, of course, the king of death, meaning spiritual death, doesn't see us.

60
00:06:07,557 --> 00:06:08,197
That's what it means.

61
00:06:09,338 --> 00:06:18,949
Now, the purpose of this meditation is, first of all, to encourage that sort of detachment from the body, or non-attachment, should I say, non-attachment.

62
00:06:18,968 --> 00:06:25,797
So you can understand that people who are in the medical profession, I mean, they have to have a certain detachment to...

63
00:06:27,041 --> 00:06:29,125
to what the body is capable of manufacturing.

64
00:06:30,906 --> 00:06:34,391
It's also a way of cooling erotic impulses, right?

65
00:06:34,451 --> 00:06:36,194
So this is important if you're a monastic.

66
00:06:37,115 --> 00:06:47,148
So basically, when something erotic arises in the mind, when you see the impurities of that body, it tends to scupper it.

67
00:06:47,168 --> 00:06:49,170
It tends to take the imagination.

68
00:06:49,430 --> 00:06:52,896
The imagination disappears on the wonderful of it.

69
00:06:52,956 --> 00:06:56,019
So as you know, beauty is skin deep.

70
00:06:56,471 --> 00:07:01,677
And that's part of it too, that we don't worry about our physical beauty anymore.

71
00:07:02,017 --> 00:07:03,178
The body is the body.

72
00:07:03,199 --> 00:07:04,139
It's just the way it is.

73
00:07:04,160 --> 00:07:06,723
You have to be, as they say, happy in our skin.

74
00:07:12,269 --> 00:07:16,954
So I'm going to now read through these 32 parts.

75
00:07:18,134 --> 00:07:20,817
Okay?

76
00:07:20,838 --> 00:07:25,483
And the idea is that as I mention a word, the image...

77
00:07:25,766 --> 00:07:31,452
the relationship will come to mind, and you want to get in touch with that reaction, right?

78
00:07:31,552 --> 00:07:35,557
Because that reaction is telling us how we relate to that part of the body.

79
00:07:36,158 --> 00:07:38,420
So it could be equanimous, it could be no reaction.

80
00:07:38,841 --> 00:07:45,326
On the other hand, there could be some level of repulsiveness, disgust, et cetera, right?

81
00:07:45,507 --> 00:07:46,548
So you've got to accept that.

82
00:07:46,569 --> 00:07:50,392
You've got to let that come up, you see, and just acknowledge it, okay?

83
00:07:50,413 --> 00:07:54,677
So this is the part of the exercise

84
00:07:54,978 --> 00:07:58,442
of getting in touch with our relationship to the body.

85
00:07:58,702 --> 00:07:58,983
Okay?

86
00:07:59,504 --> 00:08:07,874
So I'm going to read these parts, the Buddha's own 32 parts, I think he said.

87
00:08:08,173 --> 00:08:09,055
Yeah, something like that.

88
00:08:11,177 --> 00:08:15,382
Okay, so if we just settle for a moment, you see.

89
00:08:24,137 --> 00:08:25,821
Okay, so here's the first one.

90
00:08:28,326 --> 00:08:39,405
Hair on the head, the scalp, dandruff.

91
00:08:39,426 --> 00:08:40,148
Body hair.

92
00:08:46,298 --> 00:08:47,360
Nails.

93
00:08:53,938 --> 00:09:15,035
Teeth Skin Muscles, flesh

94
00:09:24,870 --> 00:09:25,552
Tinnitus.

95
00:09:34,427 --> 00:09:35,190
Bones.

96
00:09:43,625 --> 00:09:44,787
Bone marrow.

97
00:09:55,414 --> 00:10:15,263
kidneys, heart, liver,

98
00:10:25,402 --> 00:10:48,894
Diaphragm Spleen Lungs

99
00:10:59,152 --> 00:11:00,313
Intestines.

100
00:11:10,672 --> 00:11:11,413
Bowels.

101
00:11:21,250 --> 00:11:23,033
Undigested food.

102
00:11:31,567 --> 00:11:52,107
species bio phlegm

103
00:12:01,538 --> 00:12:23,614
pus blood sweat

104
00:12:33,246 --> 00:12:58,090
Fat Tears Saliva

105
00:13:08,582 --> 00:13:10,225
Nasal mucus.

106
00:13:25,143 --> 00:13:27,365
Synovial fluid.

107
00:13:29,106 --> 00:13:30,129
That's around the joints.

108
00:13:36,856 --> 00:13:37,256
Lymph.

109
00:13:46,282 --> 00:14:07,841
Now, just go back to the one that gave you the most sense of disgust or dislike, call it what you wish.

110
00:14:08,380 --> 00:14:16,288
Just go back to it and just get in touch with that feeling, with that reaction.

111
00:14:34,173 --> 00:14:41,203
and just see if you can change your view of it, maybe from a chemical point of view, a functional point of view.

112
00:14:58,650 --> 00:15:02,576
So then he reminds us of the drawbacks

113
00:15:03,451 --> 00:15:04,273
of the body.

114
00:15:06,155 --> 00:15:15,855
So he also asks us to contemplate the fact that there are diseases and he holds a whole list here which is not at all comprehensive of course.

115
00:15:15,875 --> 00:15:25,053
Diseases of the eye, the inner ear, the nose, the tongue, the body, the head, the outer ear, the mouth, the teeth and the lips.

116
00:15:25,894 --> 00:15:55,091
cough, asthma, catarrh, inflammation, fever, stomachache, fainting, dysentery, gastric pain, cholera, leprosy, boils, eczema, tuberculosis, epilepsy, herpes, itch, scabs, smallpox, scabies, hemorrhage, diabetes, piles, pimples and ulcers, affliction stemming from disorders of bile, phlegm,

117
00:15:55,662 --> 00:16:13,735
wind or their conjunction, afflictions caused by change in the weather, by not taking care of yourself, by overexertion or as a result of past deeds, cold, heat, hunger, thirst, defecation and urination.

118
00:16:14,517 --> 00:16:17,501
So there's a nice little list to contemplate.

119
00:16:17,802 --> 00:16:20,085
what the body is capable of giving us.

120
00:16:21,067 --> 00:16:37,369
So there are these two parts, but the main part is to bring parts of the body to mind that we find in some way difficult to be with equanimously and just keep working on it until that sense of disgust disappears.

121
00:16:39,572 --> 00:16:47,082
Disgust, of course, is a natural reaction, but I think it should be when you put something horrible in the mouth.

122
00:16:50,100 --> 00:16:57,778
Now, he gave this teaching to a group of monks, you see, or to the sangha that was at the monastery in Veselin.

123
00:16:58,520 --> 00:16:59,503
And then he went off.

124
00:16:59,744 --> 00:17:02,650
The Buddha went off to do two weeks by himself.

125
00:17:02,951 --> 00:17:06,861
He often went off for quiet abidings.

126
00:17:07,718 --> 00:17:17,527
So you can imagine that, you know, there comes a time when he's got lots of visitors, lots of monks, you know, and he just needs to get away for a bit of a rest.

127
00:17:17,547 --> 00:17:20,308
And what he would do is go off into the forest by himself.

128
00:17:22,090 --> 00:17:23,352
Just for a couple of weeks, you know.

129
00:17:23,971 --> 00:17:32,839
Anyway, having given this talk to the monks, he comes back and he says, Ananda, why does the Sangha of monks look so depleted?

130
00:17:32,960 --> 00:17:34,320
In other words, where have all the monks gone?

131
00:17:35,962 --> 00:17:37,624
And he says, well, because Lord,

132
00:17:38,042 --> 00:17:54,442
with many lines of reasoning, gave monks a talk on the unattractiveness of the body, spoke in praise of the perception of unattractiveness, spoke in praise of the development of the perception of unattractiveness.

133
00:17:54,884 --> 00:18:02,432
And the monks, thinking, oh, the Blessed One, with many lines of reasoning, has given a talk on the unattractiveness of the body.

134
00:18:03,213 --> 00:18:06,278
They remained committed to the development of it,

135
00:18:06,645 --> 00:18:15,760
in many modes and manners, they, ashamed, repelled, and disgusted with the body, sought for an assassin.

136
00:18:16,722 --> 00:18:19,426
In one day, ten monks took the knife.

137
00:18:20,208 --> 00:18:22,451
In one day, twenty monks took the knife.

138
00:18:23,053 --> 00:18:25,676
And in one day, thirty monks took the knife.

139
00:18:26,278 --> 00:18:28,501
It would be good, Lord, if

140
00:18:28,819 --> 00:18:35,828
you could explain another method so that this Sangha of monks might be established in understanding.

141
00:18:36,450 --> 00:18:45,682
So I can't imagine how he felt when he came back from his rest to find that all these monks had committed suicide because of his teachings.

142
00:18:46,624 --> 00:18:54,894
So what he does is he gives them the exercise of practicing these absorptions.

143
00:18:55,279 --> 00:19:01,810
But there's another way that we can relate to the body, which, shall we say, balances this whole business.

144
00:19:02,792 --> 00:19:04,976
And that is by offering gratitude.

145
00:19:05,678 --> 00:19:06,218
Okay.

146
00:19:07,099 --> 00:19:11,887
So this little exercise, what we're going to do is go through the body in a different way.

147
00:19:12,424 --> 00:19:18,755
And we're going to recognise what the body does for us, right?

148
00:19:18,795 --> 00:19:22,681
So, for instance, the skin is our outer protection, okay?

149
00:19:23,182 --> 00:19:31,394
It does other things too, but whatever comes to mind, whatever comes to mind that a particular part of the body does, you say thank you, right?

150
00:19:31,934 --> 00:19:32,997
And that's all you do.

151
00:19:33,237 --> 00:19:34,920
All you're going to do is say thank you.

152
00:19:35,601 --> 00:19:39,646
And you just keep saying thank you, right, to all the parts of the body, okay?

153
00:19:40,218 --> 00:19:46,948
So if we just settle for a moment and then I'll suggest another way that you can go through the body and do this.

154
00:20:07,936 --> 00:20:09,819
So just starting at the top of the head,

155
00:20:10,086 --> 00:20:18,061
And just come down the body and just say thank you to our protecting skin.

156
00:20:27,922 --> 00:20:29,664
All the way down to the toes.

157
00:20:44,528 --> 00:20:47,692
It's like you're showering yourself with gratitude.

158
00:20:54,500 --> 00:20:56,342
Coming back to the top of the head there.

159
00:20:56,382 --> 00:21:00,446
And just sink into the skull, the bones.

160
00:21:01,508 --> 00:21:04,852
And just saturate it with your gratitude.

161
00:21:05,413 --> 00:21:06,034
Thank you.

162
00:21:06,094 --> 00:21:07,414
Thank you.

163
00:21:07,474 --> 00:21:07,816
Thank you.

164
00:21:12,480 --> 00:21:13,843
All the way down the body.

165
00:21:14,329 --> 00:21:23,040
just following the skeleton.

166
00:21:23,060 --> 00:21:33,434
It holds the marrow, of course, where all the blood cells are created, all the way down to the toes.

167
00:21:43,759 --> 00:21:54,769
And if we come back to the top of the head, and this time we sink into the brain, and we just keep saying thank you.

168
00:21:56,614 --> 00:21:59,862
And then follow the nervous system all down the body.

169
00:22:15,130 --> 00:22:16,731
All the way down to the toes.

170
00:22:28,227 --> 00:22:30,130
And coming back to the top of the head.

171
00:22:32,913 --> 00:22:36,738
And this time we go into the muscles of the face.

172
00:22:36,758 --> 00:22:39,122
Just massaging them with this gratitude.

173
00:22:41,464 --> 00:22:44,749
And then follow the musculature all the way down to the toes.

174
00:22:51,242 --> 00:22:54,526
It's massaging your muscle with gratitude.

175
00:23:13,665 --> 00:23:19,511
And then coming back to the heart in the body.

176
00:23:24,554 --> 00:23:26,637
filling the heart with gratitude.

177
00:23:34,550 --> 00:23:43,086
And then just follow the blood every which way, just saying thank you, feeding the body.

178
00:24:04,008 --> 00:24:28,259
and coming back to the head offering gratitude to our eyes and to the ears and to the nose

179
00:24:37,336 --> 00:24:40,361
To the tongue and teeth, these are all our senses.

180
00:24:49,114 --> 00:24:50,955
And to the larynx, the voice.

181
00:25:00,951 --> 00:25:04,676
Thinking into the chest, say thank you to all the organs there.

182
00:25:28,450 --> 00:25:33,599
Coming down into the midriff, the stomach, liver area, all the various organs.

183
00:26:13,067 --> 00:26:15,905
down into the abdomen, the various systems.

184
00:26:51,931 --> 00:26:53,654
Thank you to our hands.

185
00:27:06,102 --> 00:27:07,644
And thank you to our feet.

186
00:27:19,605 --> 00:27:25,433
And finally, thank you to the whole body, the whole physical organism.

187
00:27:33,987 --> 00:27:41,156
So this organism made up of billions of cells, some guest cells, billions of guest cells.

188
00:27:43,279 --> 00:27:45,522
They can't be but jumping for joy.

189
00:27:45,743 --> 00:27:48,027
Finally, their work has been acknowledged.

190
00:27:50,317 --> 00:27:57,748
So this exercise then balances the unattractiveness of the body.

191
00:27:58,808 --> 00:28:00,872
We feel grateful that we have a body.

192
00:28:04,477 --> 00:28:09,103
So now you can spend as much as you want on this exercise.

193
00:28:09,222 --> 00:28:13,729
I'll put a PDF up on the website.

194
00:28:14,390 --> 00:28:18,115
But actually, once you know what you're doing,

195
00:28:18,787 --> 00:28:29,780
It's just a two-minute job, you know, just in the morning, just to acknowledge that there are parts of the body that we don't particularly like, etc., just to spend a moment thanking it.

196
00:28:30,521 --> 00:28:35,146
And that can't be doing us harm, can it?

197
00:28:35,166 --> 00:28:43,196
All those negative feelings, all that negative relationship we have with the body can't be doing it any good, right?

198
00:28:43,998 --> 00:28:47,663
It's a way of suppressing what the body does.

199
00:28:50,073 --> 00:28:53,378
So this brings us to the end of this lovely little exercise.

200
00:28:54,601 --> 00:29:00,952
I can only hope that it will further you on your path to complete and total liberation.

201
00:29:01,634 --> 00:29:03,778
Sadhu, sadhu, sadhu.

